tut constitutionnel du Québec. Ses écrits portent sur l’identité canadienne-française, le fédéralisme, le nationalisme ainsi que la francophonie ontarienne et internationale. D’une très grande actualité, ces travaux témoignent des transformations de l’identité canadienne-française depuis les années 1950.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFrench-CanadiansxPolitical activityxHistory2DLC. 0aNationalismzQuébec (Province)xSociological aspects2DLC. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aCardinal, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNormand, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNormand, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9782763756479?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9782763756479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9782763756479/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles